<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="normal" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

<title>The Normal Distribution</title>
<introduction>
<p>
  The Binomial distribution introduced in the previous section is one of the simplest probability distributions to understand 
  because it describes the number of successes in a fixed number of independent trials. 
  However, one of the most important probability distributions in statistics is the <em>Normal distribution</em>, 
  also known as the <em>Gaussian distribution</em> or the <em>bell-shaped distribution</em>. 
  Many natural, biological and social measurements can be described, or approximated, 
  by a Normal distribution, making it one of the most widely used statistical models.
</p>
<p>
  The Normal distribution is defined by two parameters:
  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        The <em>Mean</em> (<m>\mu</m>), which determines the centre or location of the distribution.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        The <em>Standard Deviation</em> (<m>\sigma</m>), which determines the spread of the distribution.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</p>
<p>
  In statistical notation, a normally distributed variable is written as
  <md>
    X \sim Normal(\mu,\sigma)
  </md>, 
  indicating that the variable follows a Normal distribution with mean <m>\mu</m> and standard deviation <m>\sigma</m>.
</p>
<p>
  Although R provides separate functions for working with the Normal distribution, namely <c>dnorm()</c>, 
  <c>pnorm()</c>, <c>qnorm()</c> and <c>rnorm()</c>, you do not need to remember these function names 
  when using R-Instat. Instead, open the <em>Show Model</em> dialog through 
  <em>Model &gt; Probability Distributions &gt; Show Model...</em> and select <em>Normal</em> 
  from the <em>Distribution</em> drop-down list. 
  R-Instat automatically generates the appropriate R command, 
  which can be viewed by selecting <em>To Script</em> before running the dialog or by viewing the 
  R Script window.
</p>
<p>
  When <em>Normal</em> is selected as the distribution, the <em>Distribution Parameters</em> 
  section displays two input boxes: <em>Mean</em> and <em>Standard Deviation</em>. 
  These parameters control the position and shape of the distribution.
</p>
<figure xml:id="fig-normal-dialog">
  <caption>Show Model dialog with the Normal distribution selected.</caption>
  <image source="images\intro-to_probability\show_model_normal.png"/>
</figure>
<p>
  To explore the Normal distribution, open the <em>Show Model</em> dialog and select 
  <em>Normal</em> as the distribution. Leave the default parameter values of Mean = 0 
  and Standard Deviation = 1. Select <em>Graph</em> as the output and click <em>OK</em>. 
  The resulting graph is shown in Figure <xref ref="fig-normdist"/>.
</p>
<figure xml:id="fig-normdist">
  <caption>The Normal distribution with mean 0 and standard deviation 1.</caption>
  <image source="images/normdist.png"/>
</figure>
<p>
  The graph has the familiar bell-shaped appearance that gives the Normal distribution its common name, the <em>bell curve</em>. 
  Unlike the Binomial distribution, which is discrete and consists of separate possible outcomes, 
  the Normal distribution is continuous. 
  This means that any value within its range is possible. 
  For example, measurements such as temperature, height, 
  weight and rainfall can take values such as 23, 23.5 or 23.57, 
  making the Normal distribution an appropriate model for many continuous variables.
</p>
<p>
  One advantage of using R-Instat is that you can immediately investigate how changing the distribution parameters affects the graph. Modify the Mean while keeping the Standard Deviation constant and observe the resulting graph.
</p>
<figure xml:id="fig-normmean">
  <caption>Normal distributions with different means but the same standard deviation.</caption>
  <image source="images/normmean.png"/>
</figure>
<p>
  Changing the Mean moves the entire distribution to the left or right without changing its overall shape. Increasing the Mean shifts the centre of the distribution to larger values, while decreasing the Mean shifts it to smaller values. The spread of the distribution remains unchanged because the Standard Deviation has not been altered.
</p>
<p>
  Next, keep the Mean fixed and change the Standard Deviation to different values.
</p>
<figure xml:id="fig-normsd">
  <caption>Normal distributions with the same mean but different standard deviations.</caption>
  <image source="images/normsd.png"/>
</figure>
<p>
  The Standard Deviation controls the spread of the distribution. Larger values produce a wider and flatter curve, indicating greater variability in the observations. Smaller values produce a narrower and taller curve, indicating that the observations are concentrated more closely around the Mean. Although the shape changes, the total area under the curve always remains equal to one because the graph represents a probability distribution.
</p>
<p>
  The <em>Show Model</em> dialog can also be used to calculate probabilities and quantiles for the Normal distribution in exactly the same way as described for the Binomial distribution. Simply select the required tab, choose <em>Normal</em> as the distribution and specify the appropriate values for the Mean and Standard Deviation. R-Instat automatically performs the required calculations and generates the corresponding R code.
</p>
<p>
  An important property of the Normal distribution is the relationship between the Mean and the Standard Deviation. 
  Regardless of the actual parameter values:
  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Approximately 68% of observations lie within one Standard Deviation of the Mean.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Approximately 95% of observations lie within two Standard Deviations of the Mean.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Approximately 99.7% of observations lie within three Standard Deviations of the Mean.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</p>
<p>
  This relationship is commonly known as the <em>68 - 95 - 99.7 Rule</em> or the <em>Empirical Rule</em>. 
  It provides a useful way of understanding how observations are distributed around the Mean and is illustrated 
  in Figures <xref ref="fig-sdnorm1"/> and <xref ref="fig-sdnorm2"/>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="fig-sdnorm1">
  <caption>Illustration of the 68 - 95 - 99.7 rule showing the probability within one standard deviation of the Mean.</caption>
  <image source="images/sdnorm1.png"/>
</figure>

<figure xml:id="fig-sdnorm2">
  <caption>Illustration of the 68 - 95 - 99.7 rule showing the probability within two standard deviations of the Mean.</caption>
  <image source="images/sdnorm2.png"/>
</figure>
<p>
  The Normal distribution forms the basis of many statistical methods introduced later in this book. Developing an understanding of how its Mean and Standard Deviation influence its shape will help you interpret statistical analyses and use R-Instat more effectively.
</p>
</introduction>

<xi:include href="subsections/normal/subsec-density.ptx"/>
</section>